acceptance:
**User story:** As a developer opening the document graph, I want a structured integrity panel that groups real document problems by kind and points me at the files to fix, so I can triage a noisy graph quickly and confirm when it is healthy.

**Acceptance criteria:**

1. `docgraph.Graph.Warnings` (or a sibling `Issues` field) is a typed slice with `Kind`, `Path`, `ID`, `Message`, and optional `RelatedPath`. Kinds include at minimum: `duplicate_id`, `parse_error`, `missing_dep`, `id_path_missing`, `id_path_mismatch`, `required_root_missing`, `cascade_unknown`.
2. GraphQL schema exposes `DocGraph.issues: [GraphIssue!]!` with the same fields. The existing string `warnings` either stays (rendered from issues) or is deprecated with a schema comment.
3. Unit tests in `cli/internal/docgraph/docgraph_test.go` cover each issue kind: fixtures that produce exactly one instance of that kind and assert the typed output.
4. `/graph` page renders an **Integrity** panel when `issues.length > 0`:
   - grouped by `kind` with a count per group;
   - each row shows path, id, and message;
   - path links to the document viewer (reuses existing documents route);
   - total-issues badge appears next to the page title.
5. With zero issues, neither the panel nor the badge renders, and the graph view is visually identical to a healthy graph today.
6. Duplicate-ID rows show both paths and a "copy suggested unique ID" button; the suggestion is deterministic (same input → same output) and a unit test asserts the suggestion function's stability.
7. `ddx docs audit` (or `ddx doctor docs`) CLI command prints the same issue list grouped by kind, exits 0 if empty and 1 if any issues present. Integration test asserts exit codes and grouped output.
8. Playwright e2e:
   - navigates to `/graph` on a fixture repo with one seeded duplicate-id pair and one missing-dep target;
   - asserts the Integrity panel shows groups "Duplicate ID (1)" and "Missing dep target (1)";
   - expands the Duplicate ID group and asserts both paths are visible;
   - clicks the first path and asserts navigation to the documents route for that file;
   - on a clean fixture repo, asserts neither the panel nor the badge is present.

**Dependency:** best sequenced after `ddx-12cae4dd` lands so the fixture repos are not polluted by `.claude/worktrees` noise, but implementation does not block on it — the two can proceed in parallel and this bead's tests use synthetic fixtures.

description:
## Problem

RouteRequest struct at cli/internal/agent/types.go:330-337 has no Provider field:

    type RouteRequest struct {
        Profile         string // cheap, standard, smart
        ModelRef        string // logical catalog ref or alias
        ModelPin        string // exact concrete model string
        Effort          string
        Permissions     string
        HarnessOverride string
    }

NormalizeRouteRequest (cli/internal/agent/routing.go:305-312) only translates --provider when it names a known harness (or alias like 'local'); otherwise it DROPS the value entirely:

    } else if flags.Provider != '' {
        resolved := resolveHarnessAlias(flags.Provider)
        // Only treat as harness override if it names a registered harness;
        // otherwise it's a ddx-agent provider name (e.g. 'vidar') and
        // should not constrain harness selection.
        if _, ok := builtinHarnesses[resolved]; ok {
            req.HarnessOverride = resolved
        }
        // else: provider silently discarded — RouteRequest carries no provider preference
    }

Result: the rest of the routing engine (candidate planning, scoring, escalation) has no way to see --provider. The --provider flag 'works' today only because RunOptions.Provider is passed directly to resolveEmbeddedAgentProvider at agent_runner.go:93 via a parallel code path that bypasses routing.

This is the root cause of every gap SD-015 calls 'provider soft preference' — Mode 2 step 3 ('pick best provider'), Mode 3 ('provider soft preference'), Mode 5 ('--provider P alone'). None can work without a Provider field in RouteRequest.

## Fix

1. Add Provider string field to RouteRequest (types.go:330). Document its semantics: 'preferred provider name (soft affinity for candidate ranking; hard affinity when combined with --harness or when it's the only input)'.

2. Update NormalizeRouteRequest (routing.go:305-312) to ALWAYS capture flags.Provider into req.Provider regardless of harness naming. Keep the existing harness-alias resolution separately.

3. Teach scoreCandidate (routing.go:471-550) to award a bonus when the candidate's concrete provider matches req.Provider (SD-015 'Provider as Modifier' soft preference).

4. Teach BuildCandidatePlans (routing.go:27+) to preserve the discovered provider on each CandidatePlan so scoreCandidate has the data to do the comparison.

5. Regression test: RouteRequest{Provider: 'vidar-omlx', ModelPin: 'Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-4bit'} produces a candidate plan that ranks vidar-omlx (embedded-openai surface) above other providers with the same model, and CandidatePlan carries Provider='vidar-omlx'.

## Files likely touched

- cli/internal/agent/types.go — RouteRequest + CandidatePlan.Provider (CandidatePlan already has Provider per earlier work)
- cli/internal/agent/routing.go — NormalizeRouteRequest, scoreCandidate, evaluateCandidate (for assigning Provider to plans)
- cli/internal/agent/routing_test.go — Provider propagation + soft-preference scoring tests
- cli/cmd/agent_cmd.go — ensure --provider reaches both RouteFlags.Provider and RunOptions.Provider as today

## Depends on

None. This is the foundational fix; everything else in the epic depends on it.

Server-managed execute-loop workers produce commits that never reach the target branch. This is the default path when an operator runs `ddx agent execute-loop` without `--local`, yet the commits are silently lost.

## Evidence

cli/internal/server/workers.go:runWorker (function at line ~237) builds an ExecuteBeadExecutorFunc closure at line 248:

    executor := agent.ExecuteBeadExecutorFunc(func(ctx context.Context, beadID string) (agent.ExecuteBeadReport, error) {
        runner := m.buildAgentRunner(m.projectRoot)
        gitOps := &agent.RealGitOps{}

        res, err := agent.ExecuteBead(m.projectRoot, beadID, agent.ExecuteBeadOptions{
            Harness: spec.Harness,
            Model:   spec.Model,
            Effort:  spec.Effort,
        }, gitOps, runner)
        if err != nil {
            return agent.ExecuteBeadReport{}, err
        }
        return agent.ExecuteBeadReport{...}, nil
    })

This closure calls agent.ExecuteBead directly and returns the ExecuteBeadReport with ResultRev populated — but never calls agent.LandBeadResult. The commit sits in the worktree's branch; nothing advances the project's target branch.

Grep confirms LandBeadResult has exactly two production call sites in the entire repo:

    cli/cmd/agent_cmd.go:1372   — inside runAgentExecuteLoop's --local branch
    cli/cmd/agent_execute_bead.go:134  — interactive `ddx agent execute-bead` CLI

Neither is reachable from cli/internal/server/workers.go.

## Why this matters

Under the current help text, `ddx agent execute-loop --harness claude --model sonnet` (no --local) is the default and submits to the server. Per the help:

    --local    Run inline in current process instead of server worker
               (default: submit to server)

Every operator who follows the documented default pattern is running workers whose commits will not land. The loop reports ExecuteBeadStatusSuccess to the tracker (CloseWithEvidence fires), closes the bead, and writes tracker events — but `git log main` never sees the commit.

## Scope of this bead

This bead is a P0 CALL-SITE FIX. It does NOT redesign the merge orchestration — that is covered by ddx-8746d8a6 (the meta-bead). This bead closes the acute correctness gap: ensure the server path, today, lands commits the same way the --local path does, so work stops being silently dropped while the meta redesign is in flight.

## The fix (interim, pre-meta)

Mirror the --local closure's land sequence into workers.go:248. After agent.ExecuteBead returns a non-nil result, call agent.LandBeadResult + agent.ApplyLandingToResult before returning the ExecuteBeadReport. Pseudocode:

    res, err := agent.ExecuteBead(...)
    if err != nil && res == nil {
        return agent.ExecuteBeadReport{}, err
    }
    if res != nil {
        if landing, landErr := agent.LandBeadResult(
            m.projectRoot, res, &agent.RealOrchestratorGitOps{}, agent.BeadLandingOptions{},
        ); landErr == nil {
            agent.ApplyLandingToResult(res, landing)
        } else if err == nil {
            err = landErr
        }
    }
    if err != nil {
        return agent.ExecuteBeadReport{}, err
    }
    return agent.ExecuteBeadReport{...populated from res...}, nil

This IS the same merge-instead-of-rebase pattern the meta redesign will replace — but it at least stops losing work today. The meta redesign (ddx-8746d8a6) will rewrite this call site entirely, so consider this a stopgap until the coordinator goroutine is in place.

## Regression test

cli/internal/server/workers_test.go: start a WorkerManager against a temp project, submit a worker that produces a single commit, wait for the worker to finish, assert git log on the temp project's target branch shows the worker's commit is in the history and referenced by the worker's LastResult.ResultRev. The test must fail against the current code (commit is NOT in main's history post-worker-exit) and pass after the fix.

## Dependency

Do NOT merge this fix onto main until the meta-bead (ddx-8746d8a6) design is approved. The stopgap uses the flawed `git merge --no-edit` Merge() path and will produce 2-parent merge commits. The alternative is to wait for the meta redesign's Land() coordinator and skip the interim. The tradeoff:

- Land interim fix now: stops silent work loss, accepts ongoing merge-commit noise until the meta redesign.
- Skip interim fix: silent work loss continues (every server-worker bead's commits never reach main), but the main branch history stays cleaner.

Recommendation: DO land the interim fix. Silent work loss is worse than merge-commit noise because it destroys the worker's output. Merge-commit noise is cosmetic and gets flattened by the meta redesign anyway.
